Lebanon's future is being decided now.
Lebanon's future is being decided now.
The objective of today's conference is to mobilise and join together the resources of the global community to respond to the needs of Beirut's population.
We are sending a clear message: we, the global community, Lebanon's closest friends and partners, will not let the Lebanese people down.
For the people of Lebanon, the most immediate needs expressed by those working on the ground concern healthcare, food, education, and housing. Those are the priority areas where we will act.
The efforts that we are providing will have to be supported over the long term, and we will be very attentive that the aid be efficiently delivered on the ground, to the population.

Our offer of help includes supporting a credible and independent impartial investigation of the explosion that took place on 4 August. It is a strong and legitimate expectation of the Lebanese people. It is a question of trust.

The Lebanese people are free and sovereign. It is up to the authorities of the country to act in such a way as to prevent Lebanon from falling, and to respond to the aspirations expressed by the Lebanese people in this very moment, legitimately, in the streets of Beirut.
Lebanon's future is being decided now, by Lebanon itself, and with its international partners at its side.

Any so-called information pertaining to alleged intent to register children being schooled in France based on religion, belief or origin, is absolutely false.
12 million children are already registered and the registration process will be completed including home schooling children.
The French Constitution guarantees access to education for all children, without any distinction, both as a right (public education is free and open to all) and as an obligation for the families.

The draft bill establishes a clear principle: all children must attend school. Home schooling will be limited to exceptional circumstances and require specific authorization based on clear and non-discriminatory rules.

This principle will be enforced in the primary interest of children in line with the objectives of the Convention on the Rights of the Child so as to ensure they are all offered the same educational tools and chances for their future.
It is, if anything, a mean to combat any sort of discrimination which has no place in France.
